WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.880
Awesome. Yeah, so my name is Hilary Parker. Thanks so much for coming. I'm super honored

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:19.120
to be here. This has been a really fun conference with a ton of great energy, so that's been

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:25.120
really cool. So yeah, I want to talk about using data effectively and sort of moving

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:29.520
beyond there's sort of people talk about data science and they talk about how data science

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.720
is an art. And so I want to sort of move beyond that terminology. So I'm going to talk about

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:42.000
that today. And just for a little background about me, I am a data scientist at StitchFix.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.759
I also have a podcast, Not So Standard Deviations. And I've just kind of been involved with our

00:00:47.759 --> 00:00:55.639
community for the past decade plus. So yeah, I want to talk about things that I've sort

00:00:55.639 --> 00:01:00.360
of learned from all of these different things and ideas I've been able to develop with my

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:05.680
co-host Roger on the podcast. So just a little bit of context about StitchFix because I'm

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:11.599
going to use StitchFix later as examples, some examples of my work there. So StitchFix

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:19.599
is a personal styling service. So the idea is that you come to our website, stitchfix.com,

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:25.000
and you sign up. So you fill out, you know, for the types of clothes you want. And the

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.680
idea is that you answer a bunch of questions about your style. We call it like a style

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:36.400
profile, both during onboarding and then at other various points in time. And then from

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:40.320
your perspective, you sign up, you fill out this information, and then some period of

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.720
time later, you get a box with five things in it. And those are five pieces of clothing

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:49.080
that we think you're going to like. And then you kind of keep what you want, and then you

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:55.440
send back the rest. And so those items are handpicked by a stylist. But what's happening

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:01.239
behind the scenes, and the reason we have a data science team of 120 data scientists,

00:02:01.239 --> 00:02:05.639
is that what's happening in the background is that we have a bunch of inventory. Using

00:02:05.639 --> 00:02:12.080
the data from your style profile, we will sort that inventory and determine like what

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:17.639
clothes do we think you're most likely to like. And then we order those. So we do this

00:02:17.639 --> 00:02:22.639
kind of machine learning, that's all those graphs and things that are happening. We create

00:02:22.639 --> 00:02:26.960
a list of algorithmic recommendations. Those go in front of the human stylist, and then

00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:32.520
that person selects what clothes they think they should send you. So it's called like

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:38.440
a human-in-the-loop problem, or like augmented workflow. So yeah, it's a super fun problem,

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:41.039
and I really enjoy it.

00:02:41.039 --> 00:02:45.880
So kind of zooming back out, the point of this talk, or like what I really want to talk

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:51.639
about, is the way that we do data science. And all of us are here at this conference

00:02:51.639 --> 00:03:00.399
because we really care about doing data science well. And I love this kind of paradigm from

00:03:00.399 --> 00:03:07.440
the R for Data Science book about what it looks like for us, especially our users, to

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:12.479
like participate in this data analysis, data science thing. So the idea is that you have

00:03:12.479 --> 00:03:17.720
a data set, you import it, you have to tidy it, and then you have this sort of like playful

00:03:17.720 --> 00:03:24.600
box of modeling the data, transforming it, visualizing it, and then being inspired or

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:29.960
learning new things from that process, and going through and kind of cycling through,

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:35.520
and like learning as you go. And then eventually you sort of take the exit ramp from that,

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:41.080
and you figure out some way of communicating what you've learned to another person. And

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:45.600
of course, the purpose of this graphic is that a lot of the R packages in the tidyverse

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:51.839
are meant to address different parts of this stage, right? So you have like dplyr and tidier

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:57.160
for sort of shaping and tidying the data. You have a bunch of things for visualizing,

00:03:57.160 --> 00:04:02.759
transforming, and even communicating with R Markdown and various other tools.

00:04:02.759 --> 00:04:09.479
And so if you attend the, like any sort of talk about this from Hadley or others, the

00:04:09.479 --> 00:04:13.520
idea is that, oh, actually, you know, this tidy step, we don't like to talk about it,

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:18.239
but it's actually a huge amount of the work, right? So you kind of like have this littler,

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:22.519
you know, the fun part that we want to talk about is that kind of fun exploratory analysis

00:04:22.519 --> 00:04:27.359
and the communication afterwards, but actually tidying is this huge amount of the job that

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:34.519
none of us like to talk about, right? So like one thing I love about this paradigm

00:04:34.519 --> 00:04:39.239
and sort of the way that the RStudio team and Hadley directly have talked about it is

00:04:39.239 --> 00:04:45.279
that the idea that of building the framework, of building the tidyverse and this sort of

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:50.079
opinionated API layer about what the data should look like and kind of how you should

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:56.399
be parsing results is that it's really about creating fluency and expression for that sort

00:04:56.399 --> 00:05:02.799
of playful, cyclical, you know, modeling, visualizing, transforming the data, et cetera.

00:05:02.799 --> 00:05:07.519
And so this is a quote way back in 2013 from Hadley where he says, you know, we may find

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:12.600
that the two bottlenecks in a data analysis are what you want to do and how to tell your

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.399
computer to do that. A lot of my existing work has been more about how to make it easier

00:05:17.399 --> 00:05:21.959
to express what you want. And I sort of bolded express because it is this idea of like a

00:05:21.959 --> 00:05:31.200
fluent language. And so when I think about the way that we talk about doing data analysis,

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:36.959
I was at a talk by this person, Grady Booch, who's at IBM Research, and he talked a lot

00:05:36.959 --> 00:05:42.079
about how everything is a system deep down. And I was really inspired by that because

00:05:42.079 --> 00:05:48.079
I realized, you know, when we talk about doing a data analysis, this graph really represents

00:05:48.079 --> 00:05:53.399
like a mini production system, right, where you're having data come in, you're doing something

00:05:53.399 --> 00:05:58.600
to it, but then at the end you want to have a report come out. And so really every time

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:03.040
we're doing a data analysis, we're building a little mini production system that we want

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:08.239
to work effectively. And we want it to work, we want to be able to build it quickly because

00:06:08.239 --> 00:06:11.880
building the system isn't exactly what we want to be doing. We want to be doing that

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:18.239
kind of creative, fun data analysis part. And so I felt like I learned this especially

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:23.440
well when I moved to a more kind of machine learning production type job because a lot

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:28.839
of the concepts, I'd cared so much about reproducibility in this sort of data analysis

00:06:28.839 --> 00:06:33.239
production system, and I realized that all those concepts like directly translated to

00:06:33.239 --> 00:06:40.440
machine learning production systems. So I think like thinking about our work as system

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:47.079
design is really helpful. And one of the reasons it's really helpful is because other groups

00:06:47.079 --> 00:06:52.440
have already thought a lot about system design, so there's a lot that we can learn from them.

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:57.320
And last year, two years ago at this conference, I gave a talk related to this about what we

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:03.079
could learn from like specifically the DevOps world and the operations world. I have up

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:09.440
here a book called The Field Guide to Understanding Human Error. And the whole idea there is that

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:14.679
like when someone has an error in a data analysis or like if some sort of catastrophic error

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:20.399
happens in a different system, especially in the operations world when they're dealing

00:07:20.399 --> 00:07:29.440
with systems like an airplane flying or some other kind of like high importance system,

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:34.200
they have a very disciplined way about going about talking about when a failure happens

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:38.480
in that system. And kind of the old school world was like, oh, this was due to human

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:43.559
error, but the people who think about this all the time realize that that was sort of

00:07:43.559 --> 00:07:49.880
disincentivizing for people surfacing when a system was breaking because it seemed like

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:53.839
people would be worried about like being fired or being judged or being bad at their

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:58.239
job if there was a system failure, and that's like the opposite of what you want when you

00:07:58.239 --> 00:08:02.839
are trying to keep airplanes flying safely. So they developed this whole thing about blameless

00:08:02.839 --> 00:08:06.880
postmortems, and I could go on a lot about how great these are, but the idea is to kind

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:11.880
of approach the work like if an error occurs, it's not your personal fault. It's more like

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:16.980
the system was failing you, and you had good intentions. You wanted to run an analysis

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:21.119
that worked, and it didn't, and so how can we change the system so that in the future

00:08:21.119 --> 00:08:27.299
it works for you? The other thing that groups who do a lot of system design think about

00:08:27.299 --> 00:08:33.419
are sort of opinionated frameworks. So like one example would be Ruby on Rails for web

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:38.059
frameworks where instead of just saying, hey, you can do whatever you want, and, you know,

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:41.580
every time you're designing this system, you're starting from scratch and thinking through

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:47.859
all the kind of micro decisions. Instead, it's like, okay, let's kind of have our opinionated

00:08:47.859 --> 00:08:52.380
way of setting up this system and then save our kind of creative energy for the things

00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:57.659
that we feel like are really worth it, and so last year or two years ago and kind of

00:08:57.659 --> 00:09:02.979
last year, I gave a lot of thought to this, and I have a paper about it, have talks. I

00:09:02.979 --> 00:09:07.940
would, you know, encourage you to go watch those if you want, but the idea here is that,

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:12.700
you know, I think data science should absolutely start to adopt this more actively, and then

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:16.659
I think the reason that we all are so passionate at this conference is that I actually think

00:09:16.659 --> 00:09:21.900
that our studio and specifically the Tidyverse already are doing this where it's like, okay,

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:25.820
we kind of have this opinion about how you should structure your data, but once you sort

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:29.659
of do the hard work of getting things there, then everything else is easy, and you can

00:09:29.659 --> 00:09:34.780
kind of reserve your mental energy for the fun part of data science.

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:40.020
So kind of going back, you know, like I said, this is like the system I originally was thinking

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:44.659
about, and then it's like, okay, actually, like, tidying is this huge part of the system

00:09:44.659 --> 00:09:49.539
when you zoom out more, but what I want to talk about now is that if you zoom out even

00:09:49.539 --> 00:09:55.700
more from that, like, sure, we're focused on that last mile, but actually, like, the

00:09:55.700 --> 00:10:01.340
big part of doing data science is actually getting data in the door, right, and you hear

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:05.219
about this more in, like, the statistics world where it's, like, study design and,

00:10:05.219 --> 00:10:09.059
you know, collaborating with that, but in the data science world, you really don't hear

00:10:09.059 --> 00:10:10.059
about this much.

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:13.700
Like, people kind of talk about, like, oh, the data exists in this database, and what

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:19.059
do you do with it then, but what I want to talk about now is, like, I think that some

00:10:19.059 --> 00:10:23.500
of the biggest wins I've seen in the data science world are when a data scientist actually

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:29.099
thinks about this entire process, and kind of first, you know, getting QC with the graphics,

00:10:29.099 --> 00:10:33.539
and, like, well, first of all, this is, again, kind of designing a system, and then one

00:10:33.539 --> 00:10:37.900
thing that's nice about helping, you know, kind of immediate win here is that if you're

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:42.260
more involved with the data collection process, maybe you can get the data in the door in

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:47.340
a way that it doesn't need to be tidied so much, right, so if you help, like, develop

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:51.260
the schemas and everything that, you know, is going into the data in the first place,

00:10:51.260 --> 00:10:55.780
like, maybe you won't have to, you know, spend 80% of your time doing this boring task of

00:10:55.780 --> 00:11:00.460
cleaning it up, but, you know, that's kind of, like, one practical benefit, but I want

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:06.020
to talk now about some examples of Stitch Fix, where I've seen, like, thinking holistically

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:10.659
about this broader system rather than that last mile, the ways that that has really transformed

00:11:10.659 --> 00:11:15.179
our business, so kind of going back to Stitch Fix, I was saying, you know, you create this

00:11:15.179 --> 00:11:20.739
style profile, you get five items, and then you keep what you want, send back the rest,

00:11:20.739 --> 00:11:26.299
but one of the key problems, or one of the key challenges we are facing is that five

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:31.619
clothing items, you know, for a person in some set amount of time, like, really isn't

00:11:31.619 --> 00:11:36.900
that much, so, you know, you get five things, and when you check out, like, when you decide

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:41.419
what to buy or not, we'll ask you some questions about did it fit right, did you like the style,

00:11:41.419 --> 00:11:48.460
et cetera, but, like, that's not that much data per person, and then that's further exacerbated

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:55.820
by the fact that when, like, in fashion in general, like, we're in the era of fast fashion,

00:11:55.820 --> 00:12:00.739
where an individual clothing item won't be on the racks, like, that long, I mean, you

00:12:00.739 --> 00:12:05.099
know, somewhere like, like, some of the really fast fashion, it's, like, a matter of weeks,

00:12:05.099 --> 00:12:09.260
and then, you know, for us, it's a little longer than that, but still, like, it's not,

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:15.020
you don't have one shirt usually lasting for years and years, so on top of the fact that

00:12:15.020 --> 00:12:19.020
we're not getting much data from people, like, the clothes are turning over fast enough

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:25.140
that, like, we were not able to accumulate enough data per person in order per person

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:29.619
and per clothing item to do some of the more traditional matrix factorization and other

00:12:29.619 --> 00:12:35.140
machine learning approaches, and so this was, like, something that was on apparently my

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:39.659
colleague, the person who developed this, Chris Moody, was talking about the fact that,

00:12:39.659 --> 00:12:44.020
like, basically every time someone new started on the Stitch Fix team, they would try to

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:49.140
write some sort of matrix factorization algorithm to solve this problem and would always fail,

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:54.260
and it was sort of this rite of passage for, like, joining the team, it's not exactly an

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:59.739
effective use of people's time, but, you know, everyone wanted to fix it, and so at some

00:12:59.739 --> 00:13:03.700
point, the idea got tossed around of, like, well, what if we could get more of these style

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:06.340
ratings per clothing item?

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:10.739
Obviously getting a style rating from something in person is the most effective, like, you

00:13:10.739 --> 00:13:15.700
can really see all the details, see how it fits on you, but, you know, the visual representation

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:20.659
of an item is a lot of the style signal, so there's no reason why we couldn't get ratings

00:13:20.659 --> 00:13:27.739
on that, and so, like I said, my colleague, Chris, really picked up this problem, and

00:13:27.739 --> 00:13:31.700
essentially people were, like, well, what if we created something like Tinder for clothes

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:35.659
where you could just see a clothing item and say do you like it or not and kind of swipe

00:13:35.659 --> 00:13:37.099
right versus left?

00:13:37.099 --> 00:13:43.820
So my colleague spent a year doing exactly that, he built an application first via Facebook

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:48.780
and now it's on the formal app called Style Shuffle where you essentially see a clothing

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:53.059
item and can say whether or not you like it, and you can go through very quickly and rate

00:13:53.059 --> 00:13:59.059
a ton of stuff, and this was, I mean, to say it was transformative is an understatement,

00:13:59.059 --> 00:14:02.820
I mean, all of a sudden we could do all of the matrix factorization work that we've been

00:14:02.820 --> 00:14:10.179
wanting to do, and the amount we've learned from this brand new data source has been monumental.

00:14:10.179 --> 00:14:14.539
One of the things that we've learned is kind of like how are clothes separating, right?

00:14:14.539 --> 00:14:17.700
What sorts of styles are very polarizing from each other?

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:22.099
And so one example, this is in a blog post which I've linked that you can't quite see

00:14:22.099 --> 00:14:28.340
there, is that kind of what you would call boho items versus preppy items are very polarized

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:33.780
away from each other, so those are like very two different kind of vibes that you go for

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:35.979
with your clothing.

00:14:35.979 --> 00:14:39.979
And so again, like this is just one example of the things we've learned and we've been

00:14:39.979 --> 00:14:45.419
able to incorporate into our entire recommender system, but the other thing that was really

00:14:45.419 --> 00:14:51.099
great about this project was that it also enabled like all sorts of new lines of investigation,

00:14:51.099 --> 00:14:55.539
not just for individual items, but like other people who were wanting to zoom out and think

00:14:55.539 --> 00:15:00.419
about that entire data system were able to start to pursue their own kind of research

00:15:00.419 --> 00:15:01.419
topics.

00:15:01.419 --> 00:15:06.380
And so I was one of those people where, you know, I saw that people were liking these

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:14.299
different themes of clothes and kind of clusters, and so I wanted to know like, okay, like individual

00:15:14.299 --> 00:15:19.020
items are clustering this way, but what about kind of the what's the interaction effect

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:20.299
between different items?

00:15:20.299 --> 00:15:25.099
Like when you see an entire look that is boho, what's your reaction to that versus

00:15:25.099 --> 00:15:27.539
the individual pieces?

00:15:27.539 --> 00:15:31.859
And so this was super fun because right when I started thinking about this, the ROpenSci

00:15:31.859 --> 00:15:37.380
group, and I think I'm pronouncing it right when I say you're in, from a postdoc with

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:43.020
that group, created this wrapper, this R wrapper for image magic, which is a way of kind of

00:15:43.020 --> 00:15:45.059
pasting images together.

00:15:45.059 --> 00:15:50.020
And so I was able to actually, using R and the kind of embeddings we got from these machine

00:15:50.020 --> 00:15:56.020
learning models, I was able to actually identify a bunch of like boho items and various different

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:57.020
kind of aesthetics.

00:15:57.020 --> 00:16:02.260
And so this is me, like I was able to use R to like print out essentially like baseball

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:04.460
cards of different items.

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:09.299
And then me and my colleague Natalia like went through and actually created outfits

00:16:09.299 --> 00:16:15.659
from these like empirically, like these items that we empirically saw were highly polarizing

00:16:15.659 --> 00:16:19.900
in these different kind of axes of the matrix factorization.

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:24.619
And so I was able, again, using R to create these images of outfits that I could feed

00:16:24.619 --> 00:16:28.820
right back into that style shuffle and get reactions to them.

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:34.539
So A, this is cool, like data scientists creating outfits that hundreds of thousands of people

00:16:34.539 --> 00:16:42.619
are rating, and B, that this is all using R, so like R is impacting what customers see

00:16:42.619 --> 00:16:44.820
in Stitch Fix.

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:49.340
And then again, it's just like being able to creatively think about the entire system

00:16:49.340 --> 00:16:54.219
and what clients want enabled a bunch of new data science things that was much more

00:16:54.219 --> 00:16:56.340
than that last mile.

00:16:56.340 --> 00:17:00.700
So kind of in the last five minutes, like when I talk about this sort of designing the

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:05.619
system, it might seem intimidating to say, hey, some of the biggest wins are just like

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:09.579
completely creating a new app that has a completely new data source.

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:12.939
And like once you do that, data science is great.

00:17:12.939 --> 00:17:17.660
But designing things like this is not just this kind of mythical, mysterious thing.

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:19.699
It's actually a discipline.

00:17:19.699 --> 00:17:21.939
It's something that people can learn.

00:17:21.939 --> 00:17:23.819
And there's a lot of writing on it.

00:17:23.819 --> 00:17:28.540
So this book is from Nigel Cross, which is, he's one of the premier researchers on design

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:30.420
thinking in general.

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:34.939
And I've been super inspired by reading his stuff and thinking about this in general.

00:17:34.939 --> 00:17:37.699
We've talked about it a lot on the podcast.

00:17:37.699 --> 00:17:41.099
But just some like kind of basics about design thinking.

00:17:41.099 --> 00:17:44.380
It's a very solution focused discipline.

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:45.900
You're constructively thinking.

00:17:46.619 --> 00:17:50.180
So compared to science where you're kind of diagnosing and teasing apart problems and

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:54.020
understanding the root of the problem, design thinking is much more about iterating toward

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:56.540
a solution quickly.

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:00.060
You're kind of using both your left and right brain, so your analytical mind and your more

00:18:00.060 --> 00:18:02.260
like artistic mind.

00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:04.540
And there's some really interesting stuff around.

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:06.140
It is its own way of knowing.

00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:09.699
It's not, it's a form of kind of rhetoric with sketching.

00:18:09.699 --> 00:18:12.020
And so it's not just like a thing.

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:17.500
It's actually a complete, like the, Nigel Cross talks about being this like third way

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:18.500
of knowing.

00:18:18.500 --> 00:18:21.339
There's sort of art, science, and design.

00:18:21.339 --> 00:18:24.780
And I saw this quote from him early on, and I just thought it was so perfect for data

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:28.739
science work, where it's like, you know, design ability is one of these three fundamental

00:18:28.739 --> 00:18:34.500
dimensions of human intelligence, design, science, and art form an and, not an or relationship

00:18:34.500 --> 00:18:38.420
to create this incredible human cognitive ability.

00:18:38.579 --> 00:18:43.500
So kind of like, I feel like my headline for this section is just, you know, it's not the

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:44.939
art of data science.

00:18:44.939 --> 00:18:48.579
It's not just the art of data science or the science of data science, but there's also

00:18:48.579 --> 00:18:53.219
this huge aspect, and I think in some ways the most important aspect is design thinking

00:18:53.219 --> 00:18:55.699
for data science.

00:18:55.699 --> 00:19:00.780
So you know, in terms of like what to do now, this, again, this isn't just like something

00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:01.780
you're born with.

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:02.780
It's not magical.

00:19:02.780 --> 00:19:06.339
There are ways to hone it and cultivate it within yourself.

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:11.420
The biggest one, like if I were to give my kind of instructions for what to do now, there's

00:19:11.420 --> 00:19:13.699
a bunch of really accessible reading on this.

00:19:13.699 --> 00:19:20.140
So in the podcast, we went through Nigel Cross, one of his design thinking books, and this

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:25.020
was like a photo from one of the podcast listeners, which I like love so much.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:30.459
There's also, I participated in a design sprint at work, and that was really effective.

00:19:30.459 --> 00:19:33.140
So that's something I would recommend as well.

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:37.280
There's also this really great book called Designing Your Life, which is essentially

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:42.739
applying design thinking to like designing your life, for lack of a better term.

00:19:42.739 --> 00:19:47.060
So kind of thinking about how you're spending your time, and are you like happy with, you

00:19:47.060 --> 00:19:50.819
know, the way that you're, like the choices you've made in your life.

00:19:50.819 --> 00:19:55.500
So in terms of being introduced to the concept, it's like a very personally applicable book,

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:57.819
so I totally recommend it.

00:19:57.819 --> 00:20:02.780
I think the other one that's huge is like practicing design thinking for data science

00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:03.780
problems.

00:20:03.780 --> 00:20:08.540
So in general, even within the design field, they say the only way to get good at this

00:20:08.540 --> 00:20:10.579
is to do it a lot.

00:20:10.579 --> 00:20:15.599
So we actually on the podcast talked a little bit about this, where most data science problems

00:20:15.599 --> 00:20:19.180
are like, you know, here's the data set, do something with it.

00:20:19.180 --> 00:20:23.160
But instead, I would encourage you to think like, here's an interesting problem I want

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:29.040
to solve, and how would I even go about like creating data set for this and solving it?

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:33.000
We went through one with like commute times, so understanding the variance of your commute

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:37.199
times, and it's like, okay, how would you even measure that reliably in a way that's

00:20:37.199 --> 00:20:38.959
like low touch?

00:20:38.959 --> 00:20:43.680
So Roger actually, we did this on the podcast, and Roger wrote like an epic blog post about

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:48.459
it, where like kind of just describing the entire process of coming up with it.

00:20:48.459 --> 00:20:52.760
So I would totally encourage you to read that or try to think of things in your own life,

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:57.640
and again, it might be kind of contrived, but the point is to practice.

00:20:57.640 --> 00:21:02.119
And then finally, and I wish I had a lot more time to talk about this part, but a huge part

00:21:02.119 --> 00:21:08.119
of data science, a huge part of design thinking is having empathy for the user.

00:21:08.119 --> 00:21:14.400
So being able to understand, would people want to play this kind of style shuffle game?

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:19.040
And just even like for data science, understanding what does this person need, like what sort

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:24.119
of analysis, visualizations does this person need in order to be convinced of what I think

00:21:24.119 --> 00:21:26.920
is the right conclusion from this data?

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:30.880
And so, you know, if I wanted you to walk away with one thing from this, it's that empathy

00:21:30.880 --> 00:21:33.119
is not some fixed character trait.

00:21:33.119 --> 00:21:38.359
It's actually something that you can cultivate, like it's a muscle you can strengthen.

00:21:38.359 --> 00:21:43.599
JD talked about it, but meditation is a huge way to do this, and that's been like personally

00:21:43.599 --> 00:21:47.760
very impactful for me for cultivating empathy.

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:52.040
And so if you're kind of like feeling hopeless about that part, I would just encourage you

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:56.040
to explore, like there are ways to strengthen this muscle.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.599
So with that, you know, thank you so much.

00:21:58.599 --> 00:22:01.760
I don't think I have time for questions, but I appreciate your attention.

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:01.760


